{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01F3AjK8oHbS1vdD7qRuHVay","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Story 3.2: Audit Fix Story Generation\n     2→\n     3→Status: verifying\n     4→\n     5→<!-- Note: Validation is optional. Run validate-create-story for quality check before dev-story. -->\n     6→\n     7→## Story\n     8→\n     9→As an operator,\n    10→I want `codeharness audit --fix` to generate stories for every gap,\n    11→so that compliance issues become actionable work.\n    12→\n    13→## Acceptance Criteria\n    14→\n    15→1. **Given** audit found N gaps across dimensions, **When** `--fix` is passed, **Then** N fix stories are generated as markdown files in `_bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/`, each with a user story, Given/When/Then ACs referencing the specific gap, and a suggested fix section. <!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->\n    16→2. **Given** generated fix stories, **When** saved, **Then** each story is also added to `sprint-state.json` as a backlog story entry (key matching the story filename), with `status: 'backlog'`, `attempts: 0`, and sprint counts recomputed. <!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->\n    17→3. **Given** a gap about missing logging in a specific file (e.g., `src/lib/docker.ts`), **When** the story is generated, **Then** the AC text references the specific file path and gap description from the audit dimension result. <!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->\n    18→4. **Given** `--fix` is passed but audit found 0 gaps, **When** the command runs, **Then** it prints `[OK] No gaps found -- nothing to fix` and generates no story files. <!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->\n    19→5. **Given** `--fix` is passed with `--json`, **When** the command runs, **Then** JSON output includes a `fixStories` array with `{ key, filePath, gap }` for each generated story, alongside the normal audit result. <!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->\n    20→6. **Given** a story file already exists at the target path for a gap, **When** `--fix` runs again, **Then** it skips that gap and reports it as already tracked, avoiding duplicate story generation. <!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->\n    21→7. **Given** `--fix` generates stories, **When** the stories are written, **Then** each story follows BMAD format: markdown with `# Story` header, `Status: backlog`, user story, numbered ACs with Given/When/Then, Dev Notes section referencing the audit gap. <!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->\n    22→8. **Given** `--fix` writes to `sprint-state.json`, **When** writing, **Then** it uses the atomic write pattern (write to temp file, rename) via the existing `writeStateAtomic()` function from `src/modules/sprint/state.ts`. <!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->\n    23→9. **Given** `sprint-state.json` does not exist, **When** `--fix` writes stories to state, **Then** it creates a new state with `defaultState()` and adds the backlog stories -- no crash on missing state file. <!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->\n    24→10. **Given** `--fix` is run as part of `codeharness audit --fix` (full audit flow), **When** the harness is not initialized, **Then** it exits with `[FAIL] Harness not initialized -- run codeharness init first` -- same precondition as `audit` without `--fix`. <!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->\n    25→\n    26→## Tasks / Subtasks\n    27→\n    28→- [x] Task 1: Define fix story types in `src/modules/audit/fix-types.ts` (AC: #1, #7)\n    29→  - [x] 1.1: Define `FixStoryResult` interface: `{ key: string; filePath: string; gap: AuditGap; skipped: boolean; skipReason?: string; }`\n    30→  - [x] 1.2: Define `FixGenerationResult` interface: `{ stories: FixStoryResult[]; created: number; skipped: number; }`\n    31→\n    32→- [x] Task 2: Implement fix story generator in `src/modules/audit/fix-generator.ts` (AC: #1, #3, #6, #7)\n    33→  - [x] 2.1: `generateFixStories(auditResult: AuditResult): Result<FixGenerationResult>` -- iterates all gaps from all dimensions, generates a story file for each.\n    34→  - [x] 2.2: `buildStoryKey(gap: AuditGap, index: number): string` -- generates a deterministic key from dimension + gap description hash (e.g., `audit-fix-observability-1`).\n    35→  - [x] 2.3: `buildStoryMarkdown(gap: AuditGap, key: string): string` -- renders BMAD-format markdown with user story, Given/When/Then AC referencing the specific file/function, Dev Notes with audit gap details.\n    36→  - [x] 2.4: Skip generation if file already exists at target path (AC #6). Return `skipped: true` with reason.\n    37→  - [x] 2.5: Write story file to `_bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/{key}.md`.\n    38→\n    39→- [x] Task 3: Implement sprint state integration in `src/modules/audit/fix-generator.ts` (AC: #2, #8, #9)\n    40→  - [x] 3.1: `addFixStoriesToState(stories: FixStoryResult[]): Result<void>` -- reads current sprint state (or creates default), adds each non-skipped story as a backlog entry, recomputes sprint counts, writes atomically.\n    41→  - [x] 3.2: Use `getSprintState()`, `computeSprintCounts()`, `writeStateAtomic()` from `src/modules/sprint/state.ts`.\n    42→  - [x] 3.3: Handle missing sprint-state.json by using `defaultState()` (AC #9).\n    43→\n    44→- [x] Task 4: Wire `--fix` flag into CLI command in `src/commands/audit.ts` (AC: #4, #5, #10)\n    45→  - [x] 4.1: Add `--fix` option to the audit command registration.\n    46→  - [x] 4.2: After `runAudit()`, if `--fix` is passed and gaps > 0, call `generateFixStories(result.data)` then `addFixStoriesToState(fixResult.stories)`.\n    47→  - [x] 4.3: If `--fix` and gaps == 0, print `[OK] No gaps found -- nothing to fix` (AC #4).\n    48→  - [x] 4.4: If `--json` and `--fix`, include `fixStories` array in JSON output (AC #5).\n    49→\n    50→- [x] Task 5: Re-export from barrel `src/modules/audit/index.ts` (AC: all)\n    51→  - [x] 5.1: Export `generateFixStories`, `addFixStoriesToState` from barrel.\n    52→  - [x] 5.2: Export `FixStoryResult`, `FixGenerationResult` types from barrel.\n    53→\n    54→- [x] Task 6: Write unit tests (AC: all)\n    55→  - [x] 6.1: Create `src/modules/audit/__tests__/fix-generator.test.ts`:\n    56→    - Test `generateFixStories` with 0 gaps returns empty result (AC #4)\n    57→    - Test `generateFixStories` with 3 gaps creates 3 story files\n    58→    - Test generated story contains specific file path from gap description (AC #3)\n    59→    - Test generated story follows BMAD format with Given/When/Then (AC #7)\n    60→    - Test story key is deterministic (same gap produces same key)\n    61→    - Test skips existing story files and returns `skipped: true` (AC #6)\n    62→    - Test `addFixStoriesToState` adds stories to sprint-state.json as backlog (AC #2)\n    63→    - Test `addFixStoriesToState` creates default state when file missing (AC #9)\n    64→    - Test `addFixStoriesToState` uses atomic write (AC #8)\n    65→    - Test `addFixStoriesToState` recomputes sprint counts\n    66→  - [x] 6.2: Update `src/commands/__tests__/audit.test.ts`:\n    67→    - Test `--fix` option registered\n    68→    - Test `--fix` calls `generateFixStories` when gaps found\n    69→    - Test `--fix` prints OK message when no gaps\n    70→    - Test `--fix --json` includes `fixStories` in output\n    71→    - Test `--fix` blocked by precondition check (AC #10)\n    72→  - [x] 6.3: Mock all I/O: filesystem (writeFileSync, existsSync, readFileSync), sprint state module\n    73→  - [x] 6.4: Target 100% coverage on new files\n    74→\n    75→- [x] Task 7: Integration verification (AC: all)\n    76→  - [x] 7.1: `npm run build` -- verify tsup compiles new files\n    77→  - [x] 7.2: `npm run test:unit` -- all tests pass, no regressions\n    78→  - [x] 7.3: Verify module boundaries: only barrel `index.ts` exports public API\n    79→  - [x] 7.4: Verify no file exceeds 300 lines (NFR9)\n    80→  - [x] 7.5: Verify `codeharness audit --fix` runs end-to-end and produces story files\n    81→\n    82→## Dev Notes\n    83→\n    84→### Architecture References\n    85→\n    86→This story implements FR15 (`audit --fix` generates stories for gaps) and NFR6 (generated stories follow BMAD format). It extends the audit coordinator from Story 3.1 with the `generateFixStories()` function called out in Architecture Decision 4.\n    87→\n    88→### Key Implementation Details\n    89→\n    90→**Generator pattern:** `generateFixStories()` takes an `AuditResult` (from `runAudit()`), iterates all `gaps` across all `dimensions`, and produces a markdown story file for each gap. This follows the existing `createFixStory()` pattern from `src/modules/verify/validation-runner.ts` but adapted for audit gaps instead of validation ACs.\n    91→\n    92→**Story key generation:** Each gap needs a deterministic, unique key. Use format: `audit-fix-{dimension}-{index}` where index is a sequential counter within the dimension. The key must be filesystem-safe and unique across runs.\n    93→\n    94→**BMAD format (NFR6):** Generated stories must follow the template:\n    95→```markdown\n    96→# Fix: {dimension} — {description}\n    97→\n    98→Status: backlog\n    99→\n   100→## Story\n   101→\n   102→As an operator, I need {gap description} fixed so that audit compliance improves.\n   103→\n   104→## Acceptance Criteria\n   105→\n   106→1. **Given** {gap context}, **When** the fix is applied, **Then** {expected outcome from suggestedFix}.\n   107→\n   108→## Dev Notes\n   109→\n   110→This is an auto-generated fix story created by `codeharness audit --fix`.\n   111→**Audit Gap:** {dimension}: {description}\n   112→**Suggested Fix:** {suggestedFix}\n   113→```\n   114→\n   115→**Sprint state integration (AC #2):** Use the existing `getSprintState()` / `writeStateAtomic()` / `computeSprintCounts()` functions from `src/modules/sprint/state.ts`. Read current state, add each new story key with `status: 'backlog'`, recompute counts, write atomically. Do NOT import from internal sprint module files — use barrel exports only.\n   116→\n   117→**Idempotency (AC #6):** Before writing a story file, check if it already exists. If so, skip and report. This prevents duplicate stories on re-runs of `audit --fix`.\n   118→\n   119→**No-gaps path (AC #4):** When audit finds 0 gaps, `--fix` should print a success message and exit cleanly — no files created, no state modified.\n   120→\n   121→**JSON output (AC #5):** When `--json` and `--fix` are combined, the output includes both the audit result and the fix story list. The `fixStories` array contains `{ key, filePath, gap }` for each generated story (including skipped ones with a `skipped: true` flag).\n   122→\n   123→### Existing Code to Reuse\n   124→\n   125→- `src/modules/audit/index.ts` — `runAudit()` returns `AuditResult` with `dimensions` containing `gaps: AuditGap[]`\n   126→- `src/modules/audit/types.ts` — `AuditResult`, `AuditGap`, `DimensionResult` types\n   127→- `src/modules/verify/validation-runner.ts` — `createFixStory()` as reference pattern for file writing\n   128→- `src/modules/sprint/state.ts` — `getSprintState()`, `writeStateAtomic()`, `computeSprintCounts()`, `defaultState()`\n   129→- `src/types/state.ts` — `SprintState`, `StoryState`, `StoryStatus`\n   130→- `src/lib/output.ts` — `ok()`, `fail()`, `info()`, `jsonOutput()` for output formatting\n   131→- `src/types/result.ts` — `Result<T>`, `ok()`, `fail()` for return types\n   132→\n   133→### What This Story Does NOT Include\n   134→\n   135→- No `onboard` alias — that's Story 3.3\n   136→- No interactive approval prompt — `--fix` generates and writes immediately (unlike `onboard epic` which prompts)\n   137→- No beads import — generated stories go to sprint-state.json only, not beads (beads integration is an existing pattern in onboard but out of scope here)\n   138→- No re-running of audit — `--fix` operates on the audit result already computed in the same command invocation\n   139→- No story prioritization or ordering — stories are generated in gap iteration order\n   140→\n   141→### Dependencies\n   142→\n   143→- **Depends on:** Story 3.1 (audit coordinator, `runAudit()`, `AuditResult`) — DONE\n   144→- **Depended on by:** Story 3.3 (onboard alias, must support `--fix` flag forwarding)\n   145→\n   146→### File Size Constraint\n   147→\n   148→Each new file must be under 300 lines per NFR9.\n   149→- `src/modules/audit/fix-types.ts` — ~20-30 lines\n   150→- `src/modules/audit/fix-generator.ts` — ~120-160 lines (generator + state integration)\n   151→- `src/commands/audit.ts` — ~90-100 lines (extended with --fix logic, up from 66)\n   152→- `src/modules/audit/__tests__/fix-generator.test.ts` — ~200-250 lines\n   153→\n   154→### Previous Story Intelligence (Story 3.1)\n   155→\n   156→- **`runAudit()` returns `Result<AuditResult>`** with `dimensions: Record<string, DimensionResult>`, each containing `gaps: AuditGap[]` with `{ dimension, description, suggestedFix }`.\n   157→- **`AuditGap.description` contains file paths** when applicable (e.g., `src/lib/docker.ts:42 — Missing error logging`). The fix story generator should preserve these references verbatim in ACs (AC #3).\n   158→- **Barrel imports only.** Import from `../audit/index.js` or `../sprint/state.js`, never internal files.\n   159→- **Mock all I/O in tests.** Filesystem, sprint state reads/writes all mocked.\n   160→- **Atomic write pattern** for sprint-state.json (read-modify-write with temp+rename via `writeStateAtomic()`).\n   161→- **`dimensions.ts` is 197 lines, `index.ts` is 85 lines.** Both well under NFR9 limit. New fix-generator.ts should also stay under 300.\n   162→- **`audit.ts` command is 66 lines.** Adding `--fix` will extend it but should stay under 300 if logic is delegated to fix-generator.\n   163→- **57 existing audit tests** across 4 files. New tests should not regress these.\n   164→\n   165→### Git Intelligence\n   166→\n   167→Recent commits show story 3.1 completed. The project uses:\n   168→- Commander for CLI commands (`--fix` added as `.option('--fix', '...')`)\n   169→- `Result<T>` discriminated union for error handling\n   170→- tsup for building\n   171→- Vitest for testing (2779+ tests as of story 3.1)\n   172→- Barrel exports (`index.ts`) for module boundaries\n   173→- Atomic writes for state file modifications\n   174→\n   175→### References\n   176→\n   177→- [Source: _bmad-output/planning-artifacts/architecture-operational-excellence.md#Decision 4] — `generateFixStories()` function signature\n   178→- [Source: _bmad-output/planning-artifacts/epics-operational-excellence.md#Story 3.2] — Acceptance criteria\n   179→- [Source: _bmad-output/planning-artifacts/prd-operational-excellence.md#FR15] — `audit --fix` generates stories for gaps\n   180→- [Source: _bmad-output/planning-artifacts/prd-operational-excellence.md#NFR6] — Generated stories follow BMAD format\n   181→- [Source: src/modules/audit/types.ts] — AuditResult, AuditGap, DimensionResult types\n   182→- [Source: src/modules/audit/index.ts] — runAudit() barrel export\n   183→- [Source: src/modules/verify/validation-runner.ts#createFixStory] — Reference pattern for fix story file writing\n   184→- [Source: src/modules/sprint/state.ts] — getSprintState(), writeStateAtomic(), computeSprintCounts()\n   185→- [Source: src/commands/audit.ts] — Existing audit command to extend with --fix\n   186→\n   187→### Project Structure Notes\n   188→\n   189→- New files: `src/modules/audit/fix-types.ts`, `src/modules/audit/fix-generator.ts`, `src/modules/audit/__tests__/fix-generator.test.ts`\n   190→- Modified files: `src/commands/audit.ts` (add --fix option), `src/modules/audit/index.ts` (add barrel exports)\n   191→- No patches created in this story\n   192→- Module follows existing conventions: barrel exports, Result<T> returns, <300 line files\n   193→\n   194→<!-- CODEHARNESS-PATCH-START:story-verification -->\n   195→## Verification Requirements\n   196→\n   197→- [ ] Showboat proof document created (`docs/exec-plans/active/3-2-audit-fix-story-generation.proof.md`)\n   198→- [ ] All acceptance criteria verified with real-world evidence\n   199→- [ ] Test coverage meets target (100% of all new code in src/)\n   200→\n   201→## Documentation Requirements\n   202→\n   203→- [ ] Relevant AGENTS.md files updated (src/modules/audit/AGENTS.md)\n   204→- [ ] Exec-plan created in `docs/exec-plans/active/3-2-audit-fix-story-generation.md`\n   205→\n   206→## Testing Requirements\n   207→\n   208→- [ ] Unit tests written for all new/changed code\n   209→- [ ] All I/O mocked (filesystem, subprocess, HTTP)\n   210→- [ ] Coverage target: 100%\n   211→<!-- CODEHARNESS-PATCH-END:story-verification -->\n   212→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01AaC2GBTKayFeJ7nzqM76bk","session_id":"1c9a200e-72ec-477b-8ec4-6d2e01a30422","uuid":"b09682a4-e5d4-4bc7-b05f-1330bb1b6884","timestamp":"2026-03-21T04:22:49.576Z"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_016Z2AzvcCh5nrCp2N7YNNmJ","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Story 3.3: BMAD Parser & Story Bridge Command\n     2→\n     3→Status: ready-for-dev\n     4→\n     5→## Story\n     6→\n     7→As a developer,\n     8→I want to run `codeharness bridge --epics epics.md` to convert BMAD stories into beads tasks,\n     9→So that the autonomous loop can pick up stories from a unified task store.\n    10→\n    11→## Acceptance Criteria\n    12→\n    13→1. **Given** a developer runs `codeharness bridge --epics _bmad-output/planning-artifacts/epics.md`, **When** the bridge parses the epics file, **Then** all epics and stories are extracted from the markdown structure, story titles, user stories, and acceptance criteria are parsed, and bridge prints per-epic summary: `[OK] Epic 1: <title> — <N> stories`.\n    14→\n    15→2. **Given** parsed stories, **When** the bridge imports them into beads, **Then** each story is created via `bd create` with `type=story`, priority is set from sprint order (first story = highest priority), description contains the path to the story file, dependencies between stories are set based on epic order, and bridge prints `[OK] Bridge: <N> stories imported into beads`.\n    16→\n    17→3. **Given** a 50-story epic file, **When** `codeharness bridge` processes it, **Then** parsing and import completes in under 10 seconds (NFR7).\n    18→\n    19→4. **Given** `codeharness bridge --dry-run` is used, **When** the bridge parses stories, **Then** it prints what would be imported without actually calling `bd create`, and exits with code 0.\n    20→\n    21→5. **Given** `codeharness bridge` is run a second time on the same epics file, **When** existing beads issues match imported stories, **Then** duplicates are not created, and bridge prints `[INFO] Story already exists in beads: <title>`.\n    22→\n    23→6. **Given** the two-layer model, **When** a story is imported, **Then** beads issue holds: status, priority, dependencies, path to story file, **And** story file holds: ACs, dev notes, tasks/subtasks, verification requirements, **And** bridge creates the link: beads description → story file path.\n    24→\n    25→7. **Given** `codeharness bridge --json`, **When** bridge completes, **Then** JSON output includes array of imported stories with beads IDs and story file paths.\n    26→\n    27→8. **Given** an epics file with no parseable stories, **When** `codeharness bridge --epics empty.md` runs, **Then** bridge prints `[WARN] No stories found in <path>` and exits with code 0.\n    28→\n    29→9. **Given** a story in the epics file has no acceptance criteria, **When** the bridge parses it, **Then** the story is still imported with a warning: `[WARN] Story <title>: no acceptance criteria found`.\n    30→\n    31→10. **Given** `codeharness bridge` is run without `--epics`, **When** the command is invoked, **Then** it prints `[FAIL] Missing required option: --epics <path>` and exits with code 2.\n    32→\n    33→## Tasks / Subtasks\n    34→\n    35→- [ ] Task 1: Implement BMAD epics/stories parser in `src/lib/bmad.ts` (AC: #1, #8, #9)\n    36→  - [ ] 1.1: Define `ParsedEpic` interface: `{ number: number, title: string, stories: ParsedStory[] }`\n    37→  - [ ] 1.2: Define `ParsedStory` interface: `{ epicNumber: number, storyNumber: number, key: string, title: string, userStory: string, acceptanceCriteria: string[], technicalNotes: string | null }`\n    38→  - [ ] 1.3: Implement `parseEpicsFile(filePath: string): ParsedEpic[]` — reads the epics markdown file and extracts epic headers (`### Epic N:` or `## Epic N:`), story headers (`### Story N.M:`), user stories (the \"As a..., I want..., So that...\" block), and acceptance criteria (`**Given**/**When**/**Then**` blocks or bulleted AC lists)\n    39→  - [ ] 1.4: Handle edge cases: empty file (return []), no stories found (return []), stories without ACs (include with empty criteria array)\n    40→  - [ ] 1.5: Implement `getStoryFilePath(storyKey: string): string` — returns the conventional path `_bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/<story-key>.md` for linking in beads description\n    41→\n    42→- [ ] Task 2: Implement bridge import logic in `src/lib/bmad.ts` (AC: #2, #5, #6)\n    43→  - [ ] 2.1: Define `BridgeImportResult` interface: `{ storyKey: string, title: string, beadsId: string | null, status: 'created' | 'exists' | 'skipped' | 'failed', storyFilePath: string, error?: string }`\n    44→  - [ ] 2.2: Implement `importStoriesToBeads(stories: ParsedStory[], opts: { dryRun?: boolean }): BridgeImportResult[]` — for each story: check if a beads issue with matching title already exists (via `listIssues()` and title comparison), if exists skip with status `'exists'`, if not call `createIssue()` with type=story, priority from story order (first = 1), and description set to the story file path. Set deps from previous story in the same epic.\n    45→  - [ ] 2.3: Handle deduplication — compare story titles against existing beads issues. Use normalized title matching (trim whitespace, case-insensitive).\n    46→  - [ ] 2.4: Handle `dryRun` mode — skip `createIssue()` call, return results with `beadsId: null` and `status: 'skipped'`\n    47→\n    48→- [ ] Task 3: Implement the bridge command in `src/commands/bridge.ts` (AC: #1, #2, #4, #7, #10)\n    49→  - [ ] 3.1: Replace the stub implementation with a full Commander.js command accepting `--epics <path>` (required), `--dry-run` (optional boolean), and global `--json` flag\n    50→  - [ ] 3.2: Validate `--epics` is provided — if missing, print `[FAIL] Missing required option: --epics <path>` and exit with code 2\n    51→  - [ ] 3.3: Validate the epics file exists — if not found, print `[FAIL] Epics file not found: <path>` and exit with code 1\n    52→  - [ ] 3.4: Call `parseEpicsFile()` to extract stories, then `importStoriesToBeads()` to create beads issues\n    53→  - [ ] 3.5: Print per-epic summary: `[OK] Epic <N>: <title> — <count> stories`\n    54→  - [ ] 3.6: Print final summary: `[OK] Bridge: <N> stories imported into beads` (or `[INFO] Bridge: <N> stories processed (<M> new, <K> existing)`)\n    55→  - [ ] 3.7: For `--dry-run`, print what would be imported with `[INFO] Dry run:` prefix, do not call beads\n    56→  - [ ] 3.8: For `--json`, output a `BridgeResult` JSON object: `{ status: 'ok' | 'fail', epics_parsed: number, stories_processed: number, stories_created: number, stories_existing: number, results: BridgeImportResult[] }`\n    57→\n    58→- [ ] Task 4: Write unit tests for BMAD parser (AC: #1, #3, #8, #9)\n    59→  - [ ] 4.1: Create `src/lib/__tests__/bmad-parser.test.ts` (or extend existing `bmad.test.ts`)\n    60→  - [ ] 4.2: Create test fixture: sample epics markdown file in `test/fixtures/sample-epics.md` with 2-3 epics and 4-6 stories\n    61→  - [ ] 4.3: Test `parseEpicsFile()` — correctly extracts epic titles and story count\n    62→  - [ ] 4.4: Test `parseEpicsFile()` — correctly extracts story titles, user stories, and acceptance criteria\n    63→  - [ ] 4.5: Test `parseEpicsFile()` — handles empty file (returns empty array)\n    64→  - [ ] 4.6: Test `parseEpicsFile()` — handles file with no stories (returns epics with empty stories arrays)\n    65→  - [ ] 4.7: Test `parseEpicsFile()` — handles stories without acceptance criteria (includes them with empty criteria)\n    66→  - [ ] 4.8: Test `parseEpicsFile()` against the actual `_bmad-output/planning-artifacts/epics.md` file — verify it correctly parses all 7 epics and their stories\n    67→  - [ ] 4.9: Test `getStoryFilePath()` — returns correct conventional path\n    68→\n    69→- [ ] Task 5: Write unit tests for bridge import logic (AC: #2, #4, #5)\n    70→  - [ ] 5.1: Create `src/lib/__tests__/bmad-bridge.test.ts` (or extend existing test file)\n    71→  - [ ] 5.2: Mock `beads.ts` functions: `createIssue`, `listIssues`\n    72→  - [ ] 5.3: Test `importStoriesToBeads()` — creates beads issues with correct args (type=story, priority, description=path)\n    73→  - [ ] 5.4: Test `importStoriesToBeads()` — sets dependencies from previous story in same epic\n    74→  - [ ] 5.5: Test `importStoriesToBeads()` — deduplication: skips existing stories with status `'exists'`\n    75→  - [ ] 5.6: Test `importStoriesToBeads()` — dry run mode: returns results without calling `createIssue()`\n    76→  - [ ] 5.7: Test `importStoriesToBeads()` — handles `createIssue()` failure gracefully (status `'failed'`, continues with remaining stories)\n    77→\n    78→- [ ] Task 6: Write unit tests for bridge command (AC: #1, #7, #10)\n    79→  - [ ] 6.1: Create `src/commands/__tests__/bridge.test.ts`\n    80→  - [ ] 6.2: Test bridge command fails with code 2 when `--epics` not provided\n    81→  - [ ] 6.3: Test bridge command fails with code 1 when epics file doesn't exist\n    82→  - [ ] 6.4: Test bridge command prints per-epic summary and total imported count\n    83→  - [ ] 6.5: Test bridge command `--dry-run` mode prints without creating beads issues\n    84→  - [ ] 6.6: Test bridge command `--json` outputs valid JSON with expected structure\n    85→  - [ ] 6.7: Test bridge command handles empty epics file gracefully\n    86→\n    87→- [ ] Task 7: Build and verify (AC: #3, #7)\n    88→  - [ ] 7.1: Run `npm run build` — verify tsup compiles successfully with updated bridge.ts and bmad.ts\n    89→  - [ ] 7.2: Run `npm run test:unit` — all tests pass including new parser and bridge tests\n    90→  - [ ] 7.3: Run `npm run test:coverage` — verify 100% coverage for new parser/bridge code, maintain overall coverage\n    91→  - [ ] 7.4: Manual test: `codeharness bridge --epics _bmad-output/planning-artifacts/epics.md --dry-run` — verify parsing output against actual epics file\n    92→  - [ ] 7.5: Manual test: `codeharness bridge --json --epics <path> --dry-run` — verify JSON output structure\n    93→  - [ ] 7.6: Manual test: `codeharness bridge` without `--epics` — verify error message and exit code 2\n    94→\n    95→## Dev Notes\n    96→\n    97→### This Story Implements the BMAD Parser and Bridge Command\n    98→\n    99→Story 3.1 created the beads CLI wrapper (`src/lib/beads.ts`). Story 3.2 created the BMAD installation and patch engine (`src/lib/bmad.ts`, `src/lib/patch-engine.ts`, `src/templates/bmad-patches.ts`). This story extends `src/lib/bmad.ts` with BMAD epics/stories parsing and implements the `codeharness bridge` command that was previously a stub in `src/commands/bridge.ts`.\n   100→\n   101→### What Already Exists (from Epics 1-3.2)\n   102→\n   103→- `src/commands/bridge.ts` — 13-line stub that prints `[FAIL] Not yet implemented. Coming in Epic 3.` and exits with code 1. Replace entirely.\n   104→- `src/lib/bmad.ts` — ~230 lines. Contains: `BmadError`, `BmadInstallResult`, `PatchResult`, `PATCH_TARGETS`, `isBmadInstalled()`, `detectBmadVersion()`, `detectBmalph()`, `installBmad()`, `applyAllPatches()`. This story adds parsing functions to this module.\n   105→- `src/lib/beads.ts` — Full beads CLI wrapper: `createIssue()`, `getReady()`, `closeIssue()`, `updateIssue()`, `listIssues()`, `initBeads()`, etc. The bridge command uses `createIssue()` and `listIssues()` from this module.\n   106→- `src/lib/output.ts` — `ok()`, `fail()`, `warn()`, `info()`, `jsonOutput()` utilities.\n   107→- `src/commands/init.ts` — ~515 lines. The bridge command is independent of init — it runs after init has already set up BMAD and beads.\n   108→- `_bmad-output/planning-artifacts/epics.md` — The actual epics file this parser needs to handle. Contains 8 epics (Epic 0 through Epic 7) with stories using `### Story N.M:` headers, `**Given**/**When**/**Then**` acceptance criteria format, and `**Technical notes:**` blocks.\n   109→\n   110→### Architecture Decisions That Apply\n   111→\n   112→- **Decision 3 (Beads Integration):** Bridge is the entry point for the two-layer model. Beads holds status/priority/deps/path. Story files hold ACs/dev notes/tasks. Bridge creates the link via beads issue description → story file path.\n   113→- **Decision 1 (CLI ↔ Plugin Boundary):** Bridge is CLI-only. The plugin does not parse epics or create beads issues directly.\n   114→- **Beads Interaction Patterns:** Always use `--json` flag when calling `bd` programmatically. Error messages include the failed command.\n   115→\n   116→### BMAD Epics File Format\n   117→\n   118→The parser must handle the actual format of `_bmad-output/planning-artifacts/epics.md`:\n   119→\n   120→```markdown\n   121→## Epic N: Title\n   122→\n   123→Description paragraph...\n   124→\n   125→### Story N.M: Story Title\n   126→\n   127→As a <persona>,\n   128→I want <capability>,\n   129→So that <benefit>.\n   130→\n   131→**Acceptance Criteria:**\n   132→\n   133→**Given** <precondition>\n   134→**When** <action>\n   135→**Then** <outcome>\n   136→**And** <additional outcome>\n   137→\n   138→**Given** <another precondition>\n   139→**When** <action>\n   140→**Then** <outcome>\n   141→\n   142→**Technical notes:**\n   143→- Note 1\n   144→- Note 2\n   145→```\n   146→\n   147→Key parsing considerations:\n   148→- Epic headers use `## Epic N:` or `### Epic N:` format\n   149→- Story headers use `### Story N.M:` format\n   150→- User stories follow the \"As a/I want/So that\" pattern\n   151→- Acceptance criteria use `**Given**/**When**/**Then**` blocks (may have multiple blocks per story)\n   152→- Some stories have a `**Technical notes:**` section\n   153→- Epic 0 exists (sprint execution skill) — include it in parsing\n   154→\n   155→### Deduplication Strategy\n   156→\n   157→When bridge is run a second time, it must not create duplicate beads issues. Strategy:\n   158→1. Before importing, call `listIssues()` to get all existing beads issues\n   159→2. For each story to import, check if a beads issue with a matching title exists (case-insensitive, trimmed)\n   160→3. If match found → skip with `[INFO] Story already exists in beads: <title>`\n   161→4. If no match → create new issue\n   162→\n   163→This is simple title-based matching. Not perfect, but sufficient for the common case (re-running bridge on the same file). More sophisticated matching (by story key or ID) can be added later if needed.\n   164→\n   165→### Bridge Command Options\n   166→\n   167→```\n   168→codeharness bridge --epics <path>          # Required: path to epics.md\n   169→codeharness bridge --epics <path> --dry-run  # Parse only, don't create beads issues\n   170→codeharness bridge --json --epics <path>     # JSON output\n   171→```\n   172→\n   173→The `--epics` option is required. If omitted, print error and exit 2. The epics file must exist; if not found, exit 1.\n   174→\n   175→### Priority Assignment\n   176→\n   177→Stories are assigned priority from their order in the epics file:\n   178→- Epic 0, Story 0.1 → priority 1 (highest)\n   179→- Epic 1, Story 1.1 → priority 2\n   180→- Epic 1, Story 1.2 → priority 3\n   181→- etc.\n   182→\n   183→This gives beads a natural ordering that matches the BMAD sprint plan.\n   184→\n   185→### Dependency Assignment\n   186→\n   187→Within each epic, stories depend on the previous story:\n   188→- Story 1.1 → no deps\n   189→- Story 1.2 → depends on Story 1.1\n   190→- Story 1.3 → depends on Story 1.2\n   191→- Story 2.1 → no deps (new epic, no cross-epic deps in automatic mode)\n   192→\n   193→Cross-epic dependencies are not automatically set. They can be added manually via `bd update` if needed.\n   194→\n   195→### What NOT To Do\n   196→\n   197→- **Do NOT implement beads-to-story sync** — that's Story 3.4.\n   198→- **Do NOT implement sprint-status.yaml updating** — bridge creates beads issues, not sprint-status.yaml entries.\n   199→- **Do NOT modify init.ts** — bridge is a standalone command, not an init step.\n   200→- **Do NOT modify beads.ts** — use the existing wrapper API as-is.\n   201→- **Do NOT use `console.log` directly** — use output utilities from `src/lib/output.ts`.\n   202→- **Do NOT add `any` types** — strict TypeScript.\n   203→- **Do NOT create the story files** — bridge only creates beads issues that link to story file paths. The story files themselves are created by the BMAD create-story workflow.\n   204→\n   205→### Scope Boundaries\n   206→\n   207→**IN SCOPE (this story):**\n   208→- BMAD epics/stories markdown parser (added to `src/lib/bmad.ts`)\n   209→- Bridge import logic with deduplication (added to `src/lib/bmad.ts`)\n   210→- Full `codeharness bridge` command implementation (`src/commands/bridge.ts`)\n   211→- Unit tests for parser, import logic, and command\n   212→- Test fixture: sample epics markdown file\n   213→\n   214→**OUT OF SCOPE (later stories):**\n   215→- Beads-to-story file bidirectional sync — Story 3.4\n   216→- Sprint-status.yaml management — handled by sprint execution skill\n   217→- Story file creation — BMAD create-story workflow\n   218→- Verification pipeline — Epic 4\n   219→- Ralph integration — Epic 5\n   220→\n   221→### Dependencies\n   222→\n   223→- **Depends on:** Story 3.1 (beads CLI wrapper — `createIssue`, `listIssues`) — DONE. Story 3.2 (BMAD installation — `src/lib/bmad.ts` module exists) — DONE.\n   224→- **Depended on by:** Story 3.4 (beads sync uses the links created by bridge)\n   225→\n   226→### New npm Dependencies\n   227→\n   228→None. The parser uses Node.js built-ins (`fs`, `path`). Beads interaction uses the existing `src/lib/beads.ts` wrapper.\n   229→\n   230→### References\n   231→\n   232→- [Source: _bmad-output/planning-artifacts/epics.md — Epic 3, Story 3.3]\n   233→- [Source: _bmad-output/planning-artifacts/architecture.md — Decision 3 (Beads Integration), Bridge Flow, Beads Interaction Patterns]\n   234→- [Source: _bmad-output/planning-artifacts/prd.md — FR33, FR40, FR41, NFR7]\n   235→- [Source: src/lib/beads.ts — createIssue(), listIssues() API]\n   236→- [Source: src/lib/bmad.ts — Existing module to extend with parser]\n   237→- [Source: src/commands/bridge.ts — Existing stub to replace]\n   238→\n   239→<!-- CODEHARNESS-PATCH-START:story-verification -->\n   240→## Verification Requirements\n   241→\n   242→- [ ] Showboat proof document created (`docs/exec-plans/active/3-3-bmad-parser-story-bridge-command.proof.md`)\n   243→- [ ] All acceptance criteria verified with real-world evidence\n   244→- [ ] Test coverage meets target (100% of all new code in src/)\n   245→\n   246→## Documentation Requirements\n   247→\n   248→- [ ] Relevant AGENTS.md files updated (src/lib module — bmad.ts parser additions, src/commands — bridge.ts)\n   249→- [ ] Exec-plan created in `docs/exec-plans/active/3-3-bmad-parser-story-bridge-command.md`\n   250→\n   251→## Testing Requirements\n   252→\n   253→- [ ] Unit tests written for all new/changed code\n   254→- [ ] Integration tests for cross-module interactions\n   255→- [ ] Coverage target: 100%\n   256→<!-- CODEHARNESS-PATCH-END:story-verification -->\n   257→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01AaC2GBTKayFeJ7nzqM76bk","session_id":"1c9a200e-72ec-477b-8ec4-6d2e01a30422","uuid":"e5d0487a-920f-4a97-9fe5-c779e21719cd","timestamp":"2026-03-21T04:22:49.785Z"}
