{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01AaC2GBTKayFeJ7nzqM76bk","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Story file created at `/Users/ivintik/dev/personal/codeharness/_bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/3-3-onboard-alias.md`.\n\n**What was done:**\n- Identified `3-3-onboard-alias` as the next backlog story in Epic 3 (Audit Command) from `sprint-status.yaml`\n- Read the epic definition (FR16: `onboard` becomes alias for `audit`), the existing `onboard.ts` (478 lines, full scan/coverage/audit/epic pipeline), `audit.ts` (127 lines, new audit coordinator), and supporting modules\n- Created the story file with 8 ACs, 6 task groups, and detailed dev notes\n\n**Verification tags applied:**\n- ACs 1-5, 7, 8: `cli-verifiable` — all can be verified by running CLI commands and checking output/exit codes\n- AC 6: `cli-verifiable` — deprecation warning can be verified by running `codeharness onboard scan` and checking stderr/stdout\n\n## Session Issues\n\n**Problems encountered:**\n- An existing file `3-3-bmad-parser-story-bridge-command.md` already exists in the implementation artifacts directory from a previous sprint's Epic 3. The current sprint reuses Epic 3 numbering but with different stories. No conflict since the new file uses the `3-3-onboard-alias.md` filename matching the sprint-status key.\n\n**Workarounds applied:**\n- None.\n\n**Risks identified:**\n- The epic definition AC3 says `codeharness onboard scan` should map to \"the equivalent audit subcommand,\" but audit has no subcommands — it's a single command. I interpreted this as printing a deprecation warning and running the base audit. This may not match user expectations if they expected scan-specific output.\n- The old `onboard.ts` exports `getLastScanResult()`, `getLastCoverageResult()`, `getLastAuditResult()`, and `resetLastScanResult()`. If any code outside `onboard.test.ts` imports these, removing them will break things. The dev notes call this out but it